The smallest honest model is:

- `Order` as the only Aggregate.
- `Money` as a Value Object on `Order.total` and anywhere payment amount/currency is compared.
- `paymentId` and `inventoryReservationId` kept as foreign references, not embedded object graphs.

I would not accept the proposed `Order` Aggregate containing full Payment and Inventory objects. Those are owned by separate systems, so putting them inside `Order` invents a consistency boundary you do not actually have.

The boundary correction is:

- Keep `confirmOrder` as an application service/orchestrator.
- Read payment/inventory state through ports or translated local records.
- Let `Order` enforce only its local rule: it cannot move from `CANCELLED` to `CONFIRMED`.
- Treat payment authorization and inventory hold as cross-system preconditions/policies, not `Order` internals.
- Persist the `Order` change in one local transaction.
- Trigger payment capture and inventory allocation as external follow-up commands/events, not by mutating foreign objects inside the same aggregate transaction.

Concretely, the domain shape should be closer to:

```ts
type Money = {
  amount: number;
  currency: string;
};

class Order {
  constructor(
    readonly id: string,
    private status: "DRAFT" | "CONFIRMED" | "CANCELLED",
    readonly total: Money,
    readonly paymentId: string,
    readonly inventoryReservationId: string,
  ) {}

  confirm(paymentAuthorized: Money, inventoryHeld: boolean) {
    if (this.status === "CANCELLED") throw new Error("cancelled order cannot be confirmed");
    if (this.status !== "DRAFT") throw new Error("bad status");
    if (!inventoryHeld) throw new Error("bad inventory");
    if (paymentAuthorized.currency !== this.total.currency) throw new Error("currency mismatch");
    if (paymentAuthorized.amount !== this.total.amount) throw new Error("amount mismatch");

    this.status = "CONFIRMED";
    return { type: "OrderConfirmed", orderId: this.id };
  }
}
```

That is the tactical minimum that genuinely helps:

- `Money` earns its cost because amount/currency agreement is business-significant.
- An `Order` Aggregate earns its cost because there is one real local invariant and a real lifecycle transition.
- Full Payment/Inventory entities inside `Order` do not earn their cost because their lifecycle and consistency belong elsewhere.

The main issue in the current routine is not lack of an object graph. It is false boundary ownership: it updates `order`, `payment`, and `inventory` as if one transaction can honestly govern all three. It cannot, given your stated ownership model.
